title: For Sale/Trade:  ISSC MK22, Copy of the FNSCAR
postcontent:
Some folks take their plinking seriously. It's not enough to just have any old wood-stocked .22 Long Rifle semi-auto in their hands. These 22s are near carbon copies of full-size combat rifles. However, they have been modified to be less expensive to buy and to shoot. To flesh out this growing field of tactical can tappers, ISSC Austria has stepped forward with its contributionthe MK22.
For fans of the FN-SCAR battle rifle, the MK22 should look very familiar. Along with the FN-style stock and receiver outline, the MK22 has many of the same features as the rifle that inspired it. The receiver is an all-metal construction, with a Picatinny-style rail system on all receiver surfaces. This includes a barrel placement for attaching FN sights. The mussle of the precision match, 16-inch barrel is cut with a 1:28 thread to accept various muzzle breaks and flash hiders.

Action: Semi-Auto
Caliber: .22 Long Rifle
Finish: Tan Ti-Clad finish
Sights: Adjustable Rifle/ 3-Dot
Barrel Length: 16
Overall Length: 36 (Stock Extended)
Width: 2.81
Weight: 6.5 lbs.
Capacity: 10 + 1, or 22+1 Rounds
Twist: 1:16 RH
Rifle Grooves: 6 

The three-position shoulder stock is adjustable for length, features a sling buckle mount and it has a two-position cheek rest that adjusts for height. The stock is fitted with a metal hinge to fold to the side with a polymer frame hook to lock the stock in the folded position for tactical training exercises. 
22-round magazine. The adjustable front and rear rifle sights can be folded down to make room for a scope. When in the down position, the sights become a three-dot pistol system. The three-dots are not terribly useful on this gun, but an interesting idea nonetheless. The charging handle is part of the patent-pending Universal Charging Adaption System (UCAS), which allows the handle to be moved to three locations on the right or left side of the gun. The hollow grip is fitted with a removable base plate so it can be used for storage. Tan finish. Take advantage of the accessory rail system to dress up the gun a bit. The lower rail provides an ideal location for the Streamlight TLR-1. The rail has plenty of room to move this compact, powerful flashlight back and forth to find the ideal location operation. The guns feel like they should be filled with water from a garden hose rather than loaded with ammunition. But shouldering and shooting the MK22 feels like you are running a "real" gun. The recoil of the MK22 is feather light, as is to be expected. The trigger is smooth, gauging out at 4-pounds, 12-ounces, with some creep after the firing pin is released. 
The greatest strength of this rifle is the flexibility of its possible applications. For an understudy to the full-throttle FN-SCAR, a customizable small game hunter or over-the-top plinker, the MK22 can do it all with panache. I've even heard folks suggest that the combat features of this rifle make it a candidate for a low-recoil self-defense option for the injured or elderly. With quality ammunition, and enough rounds fired with proper shot placement, it could do the trick. For those folks who take their .22s seriously, the MK22 is seriously fun to work with.
Manufacturer: ISSC Austria; issc-austria.com

It is definitely a head turner at the range

The ISSC-Austria Modern Sporting Rifle MK22 Rifle is engineered and precision-built in Austria incorporating the look and feel of a military-style designed rifle with the modern elements of a modern sporting rifle platform. The MK22 features an adjustable folding stock with three positions and adjustments for shoulder fit, the new patent-pending UCAS System (Universal Cocking Adaptation System), 

$750.00 Tulsa area

Those who are familiar with M4 rifles know that Daniel Defense builds one of the premier rifles produced today. Daniel Defense supplies M4's to the U.S. Military and they are a favorite among U.S. Special Forces. While everyone advertises that they build to MIL-SPEC, Daniel builds their weapons to what they term MIL-SPEC Plus.

The truth about Mil-Specs -

Mil-Specs are a convenience for the federal government when sending out bid solicitations. The do not denote a higher quality, merely the minimum acceptable level of quality and/or performance. There are Mil-Specs on nearly everything the government buys - from powdered eggs, ice cream, and chocolate to aircraft parts.

Mil-Specs are just a convenient way for the federal government to purchase things that are guaranteed to meet the minimum acceptable quality or performance level - they're a way to specify something without the need to write a complete specification every time because the Mil-Spec is the specification. 

So, when buying a weapon you intend to use for defense, I hope you'll remember that Mil-Spec is just another way for the government to spend less of your tax dollars for the minimally acceptable product - not necessarily the best product.

The S30V blade steel is designed to provide the perfect combination of durability, wear resistance, and corrosion resistance. The Tungsten DLC not only provides a non-reflective camouflaged surface, but also enhances blade hardness and reduces friction drag.

0300s handle is 3D machined G-10 in the front with a matching 3D machined titanium back. The titanium frame lock provides a secure blade lock up during use. With or without gloves, this enables a very firm grip. The solid grip enables a quick transition from forward to reverse grip time and again. Heavy jimping on the thumb ramp further enhances the grip. A 3/8-inch hex head pivot shaft nut makes field adjustments possible with minimal tools. ZT's quad-mount pocketclip enables for tip-up, tip-down, left- or right-handed carry. The 0300ST is also available in a plain edge version as the 0300.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Poor Man's AK: Norinco SKS "M" Sporter Uses AK MAGS!!!
location: South Side of Indy, Indianapolis, Indiana
postcontent:
Because of the run on guns that is going on I've decided to put this one up for sale and see how it goes. If it doesn't sell that's ok too.  The following is everything I know about this gun...

I am the 2nd owner.  I bought if from a guy in Kentucky who wanted to sell it to make room in his safe for other stuff.  He liked the gun but not as well as others.  I got the impression from him that he hadn't used it much but I don't know the "round count."  I can tell you I've shot less than 200 rounds through it.

My research into this particular SKS leads me to believe that this rifle was made after the Clinton assault rifle ban and made by Norinco for export to the civilian market. It has no bayonet or bayonet lug and has a "hunting" look to the stock.  This gun packs all the punch of the black "scary" "assault rifles" that are out of vogue in Washington (and New York, and other places) without looking scary.

For those of you who like a shorter, more maneuverable SKS, this paratrooper fits the bill. Compared to it's longer SKS cousins, this 16" barrel SKS is much more manageable. I think this would serve you well if you were to use this weapon for home defense; the standard SKSs would be too long and cumbersome for "inside" fighting. 

This SKS (like most) has a milled receiver for incredible durability. Because it was built by Norinco to use AK mags (and is not a conversion)  I call it "THE POOR MAN'S AK". For those of you who have an AK you can use the same mags (and ammo) that you're already using.  Some people have told me that SKSs tend to be more accurate that AKs, I'm not sure but I can tell you that this rifle is quite accurate. 

Like most AKs and SKSs this rifle has the adjustable front sight that allows you to (theoretically) use your iron sights for targets out to 1,000 meters. Practically speaking, my sights are spot on for up to 30 yards or so, after that distance I need the scope anyway ;-) . The front sight is nicely protected in a round shroud. For those of you who have an AK front sight adjustment tool, it will work on this SKS. 

The blonde wood stock is what came with the gun and shows some light wear but not too bad. No visible rust on the gun and the barrel's inside is very clean. I don't know if all the numbers match because when I have taken it apart to clean it I forget to check. If it is make or break for a serious buyer I'll look into it. I can tell you it functions flawlessly and I've kept it clean and lightly lubricated. This SKS also comes with it's original sling and a Tasco scope which is about the same age as the rifle. The scope mount on the rifle was engineered in such a way that you could look under it and utilize the iron sights if you so desired (see pic below). 

I'm not interested in most trades and any trades must be FTF. The only thing I might trade for would be an AK (with some $$ coming from me, for the right gun), but partial payment can be made in ammo as well (7.62 x 39, 9 mm, 40 S&W, 22 Long Rifle).  I'm only interested in up to $100 worth of ammo in partial payment.  If you are offering your gun in trade you must send me a few pictures with your offer.  

Note: The plastic mag in the pictures is for demonstration purposes only. No magazines are being offered with this gun.  If you want to purchase that magazine that would be extra and you must make sure it is legal in your locale.  

I prefer face to face near Indianapolis, any part of town except downtown or the west side (I'm hardly ever over on the west side anymore). I need to see an Indiana DL and LTCH. No paperwork, I just need to know you're not a felon or from out of state.  The buyer asserts that they are buying for themselves and this is not a "straw purchase".

If I receive an out of town bid, the bidder asserts that the gun is legal in your state/county/city.  The bidder/buyer  asserts that they are buying for themselves and this is not a "straw purchase".  Out of town buyers pay shipping and handling ($50) plus your FFL fee.  I will pay for my FFL.
